T - Talks briefly about precision and the methods they have invented, then gives directions for Ss to work in groups at their own displays trying out a method from another group. 

Ss are asked to try out the method and see if it gives a good measure of precision. They are also asked to pay attention to the steps listed. - Do they make sense, can you follow them, is this a good measure of precision?  There is no discussion of arriving at the same number as the original group or why it would be important to be able to follow the directions in the same manner as the original group.  Replicability not coded. 

Ss - begin working in groups trying out methods.  Difficult to hear. I am coding for the group closest to me. They are working with M-5 on D-3. 
Ss - working through steps in M5.

Ss cont. working through M5. There is confusion about Step 2. They call the T over to ask for clarification.  S - What do they mean "go" 15 cm? Do they want us to measure?  T - Looking at the data, what might they mean? S - gets to a place where she understands they mean 15cm in measurements on either side of the median.  T - remember to bring up that question about Step 2 in our whole group discussion. 

Ss work through method arrive at 79.17%. S - so most of the data is in the middle part of the display. The group has a discussion with the T. about this idea of data in the middle.

Group nearest finishes, Ss directed to return to seats. 

Now coding another nearby group. Working on M3. 
Ss ask for help from T. T - show me what step you are on. What are you going to do next?  S - we have found the distances, but we are having a problem adding them up. We have negative numbers. T - Can a distance be negative?          - discussion -          S - They should have added a step that said, Remove the "-" sign. That would be clearer to help show distance. T - That is called absolute value. 

Ss keep working. Complete steps. I can't hear result.

Class moves to whole group. 
T calls up Ss to discuss M2 using D10. 
The group describes the steps and shares the result - a range of 17.
T - what do you think about 17? Does it mean we are accurate? S - No, it is too big. T - What about a range of 2?  Would that be accurate?  T - So a smaller number means we are more accurate?  Ss - yes. 
T - With this method you took out the low and the high ends, then found the range and smaller is more precise. S - A range of zero would be most precise. T - What would that look like?  S - A tall tower. T - What if there was a study for a new medication and the range was zero? Would that show it worked well?  Ss - yes

T - Would this strategy help us find precision if we were measuring different things?   S - yes.  

* Coded as range and center clump as per change after last practice. This method is a range of the middle 80%. There is no discussion of total range in this segment.

New group. M5 using D3. 
The group describes the steps and shares the result - 79.17
S from group - This method doesn't work because the median was 80. It doesn't match.   T - How are you judging that not to be accurate? S - it should match the median and it doesn't use all the numbers. It cuts some off.   - discussion of whether or not all numbers are needed to measure precision. Ss come to some agreement about the idea that all numbers should be used. 

* The method is center clump but it is not discussed, so I did not code it. 
* There is no clarification about 79.17 being a percentage and a measure of the amount of data in the center.

T - Class, do you think this is a good measure of precision? 
S - I think they should have used mean as a reference point. 
T - Is there a group that has a method that used mean?

New group.  D8 / M6
As they discuss the steps, Step 2 looks at Median. 
T - We were looking for mean, but let's work through this method and we'll look at mean next. 

The group describes the steps and shares the result - 78. 
T - explain how you got 78. 
S - The median is 80. It said to + 1 (81) then -3 (78)
T - Look at step 3 / Do you think you may have missed it?  And let's talk about step 4. 
- discussion -  starts at end of segment.

Discussion continues - 
Other students clarify steps.  T leads class through method. 
S - You need to find all the data points that are 1 - 3 below or above the median, those are precise. T - Class do you agree that those numbers are precise?  Ss - yes.

T - Which group worked with mean?

New group. M4 using D6. 
The group describes the steps and shares the result - 80.5. 
There is some confusion about the steps in this method and the T leads the class through the steps together.  
This takes us to the end of the segment. Discussion is in Seg. 9. 
No coding of T. Strategies or BIs. Focus is on procedure, not what it means or what information it provides.

T - result is 80.5 what does that mean?
S - It is accurate because most of the measurements were near 80. 
T - Whose method is this?  Please go through it with us and share your thinking. S does so. 
T - What was he focusing on here?
S - He cut off the #s on the end and focused on the middle numbers because they are more accurate.

Discussion continues.  

S - Why did he take off 10%?
- discussion of mean +/- 10%.

- discussion of center clump and precision -
Range is discussed in terms of center clump. 
T - The math name for this type of method is Inner Quartile Range. 
We'll talk more about this tomorrow.

The class looked at a distribution on the board of what their classes data looked. The measurement of a desk. The teacher selected Group 1 to go first. They showed their distribution and discussed. They said theirs did not have the same range or median as the classroom distribution.

The class it looking at the distribution and says that Group 1's range is not the same as the class range and they should add a +15 on the spinner to adjust for their mistakes. They think that will make the distribution closer to what the class has. The teacher selects another group to shoe their data (Group 2).

Group 2 says their range has a high value of 97 and a low of 64. Their median is 78 and the mean is 65.5. They don't think their model is a good fit. Teacher asks what changes they would make to make it a better fit. Students say they would add a bigger negative variability. Teacher - Is this a good model if they need more values to make a good model? The group adds more variability and runs the model again.

Teacher - What are you looking for? Student - Trying to get a bigger range. They run the new model 100 times. Trying to get a better model. The range is matching. Teacher asks, you can't just go with range and know you have a better model? Student says you could have the same range but the data will be different. Our mode is now 78 it looks somewhat the same. The median is around 77. We think it is now a pretty darn good model.

The teacher asks the class to rate 1 to 10 if they think Group 2 has a good model. Most rate a 9. The teacher asks how she made the model. Student explains that 78 was her best guess. Then she looked at what percentage of the data is away from the best guess like plus 2, 5, 10 then how many. We made 14 sections.
Teacher selects another Group. Group shows distribution. (Sorry at the end of class the teacher had me take a picture of the wrong groups data. So I do not have an artifact for this discussion.)

Class looks at distribution. By looking at it they say it is a bad model. They don't like the shape of the data.  Student asks what is your range? Group replys 30. Student says but the class distribution has a range of 53. Student says you may need to add more variability you don't have enough range. Your spinner went from a -5 to +15.

Teacher - Does anyone think their percentages should change? Student- The biggest problem is their range. You have to add more to the negative side. The positive end if you take 78, which is their best guess, it has to be at the negative end because the positive side is ok.
Teacher selects next group -Group 4. They say their median is 78 and the mean is 78.2.

The teacher asks the class to put average deviation hat, ruler on their data. Teacher- Is this a good model? Student- The data needs to be spread out. There are not a lot of outliers, extremes. Student- You have to add more negative on your spinner to have the right range and the range will get higher.

Student- I think they need more of both.
Teacher- How far does your data deviate? What is your average deviation? Do you want a big or small deviation? Group 1 says theirs is 12.4. Group 2 says theirs is 12.5. Teacher- Do you think a better fit model has a small or big average deviation? Student- We want it to be small.
The teacher ends class by telling them next time they will need to improve their model to get a better fit.

In a previous lesson, students worked in pairs to invent measures of center to find the "best guess."  These methods (13 in all) were posted around the room.  The lesson began with the T referring to the methods and stating that the goal for today would be for the class to determine which method worked best  for finding the "best guess" of the T's arm length.   Ss were to work in partners and 1) Read and discuss all methods; 2) Choose a best method; and 3) Write the reasons for their choice.  Ss were given 10 minutes to for this task.  The class would discuss all methods/reasons after that.  

No T coding for this section as the information was all directions to the class.  In the last minute, students formed pairs and there was some discussion of mode for one of the methods.

Ss working in partners.   Much writing by students. General  comments - "I like it."  "it's fine."

Many reading each method aloud, but not discussing concepts. 
Some conceptual comments observed. 

More discussion of concepts in Seg. 3 as students reviewed their findings. 

No T notes in this seg. T observing Ss.

Partner work continues. 

T observing and interacting with Ss.

Ss return to desks.  Directed to share method they selected as "best" and give reasons why. 

Discussed M4 and M2.  Both mode. T - "Would mode work for all groups of data?"  Discussion of generalizability.

Cont. discussion of generalizability.  

Discussion of M10 - mode.

Discussion of M7 and M6. 

T - "Why was the mean so high?"  There is a big outlier - 1120. Discussion of how this skewed the mean.

S - " What if we take out the outlier?"  Discussion of how this would affect the mean. 
T - "Is there another measure of center that an outlier would not affect?"
Discussion of median. 

M13 discussed.
Ms - 9, 11 & 6 discussed.

T - "We found how many methods to measure center?
Review and discuss 3 methods.

T - "Consider each of the three methods.  In pairs, decide which method works best for all groups of data.  Is there one that is not affected by variations in the data?"  Discussion follows of each method and median surfaces as the "best" method for measurement of arm span length.

Discussion of 3 methods continues.  

S - "What if we took out the low and high numbers, then took the mean of the middle clusters?"  The student is talking about inter-quartile range.    Without labeling it, the T leads a discussion about this concept and what that would mean for the measure of center.
Students get out markers and white boards.  Takes time for everyone get organized.  Looking for best method to find precision, not finding data sets.

Students rotate through methods posted in the room. They are to  determine if methods work and which one works the best and why.  Working in partners. I am watching students but it is hard to hear what they are saying.  Teachers not providing assistance.
Students rotating,reading methods and discussing which is best. Return to seats at end of segment.
Teacher asks which method they liked and why. One group picked 11 and another picked 2.   Methods read and discussed. Coach takes over class discussion.
Discussion continues.  Coach asking lot of questions but not much discussion from class.
Students select method 3 as another good method.  Coach spent time asking the creators of the method what they were trying to do.  Student explanation was not clear so asked to expand thought.
Teacher selects method 4 to review.  Teacher clarifies process and what it means.
Coach creates a display on the board to visually show clustered and spread out data within center range.Good clarification and summary from student about deviation from center.
Discuss effects of outliers to data set.  Coach still in control of class, teacher makes comments.  Teacher talks absolute value and process.
Coach and teacher decide to use the "hat" in TinkerPlots to show deviation from center.

Takes over a minute to get it on the screen.  Uses example from teacher training session where they measured the circumference of a desk using a ruler and then a tape measure. Looked at data using the "hat" - both teacher and coach involved in discussion.
Teacher and coach explain more about what Tinkerplots shows.  Coach doing most of talking. Students interested in Tinkerplots and ask questions about it.

Discussion continues. The teacher asks how they would say that in the math terms they have been talking about. Students discusing in groups on how to say that using mathematical terms. Writing it on white boards.

A student said, the Theoretical probability of getting a 50/50 in chance is only going to increase the number. Teacher pressed and she said more chance. Another student said, there is a Empirical probability that you may get 50/50 or you may not get 50/50 when you increase the number of runs/spins. The teacher had it run again at 100,000 and they got 50% blue, 50% red.

Student said, more likely to get 50/50 when we increase the number of runs/spins. Teacher started to talk about how some students in the lab went further. She talked about about how they can manipulate the area of the spinner.

Teacher handing out computers. She tells the students to log in to Tinkerplots and make a red/ blue spinner. She tells them to run it 10 times and add the percents. When finished they are to turn the computers toward her.
Still logging in and creating. T - How much of the time will it land on red or blue? S- 50% of the time because it is a 50/50 spinner.

Handing out work sheet. Giving directions. Students running spins and plotting a graph. T- What happens when a chance process is repeated? She tells them to run it 10 times, plot it and add the percents.

T - What does the blue dot mean? S - It landed on the blue 6 out of 10 times or 60%. We guessed 50% of the time but when we ran it it was 60, 40, it is out of balance. T - Run it again. Did anyone get 50/50? By  chance can you get that? Students say they can by chance.

Students recording their spins on a worksheet. T - What do you notice that stayed the same? S - The spinner stayed the same. We did 10 spins every time. T- What changed? S - The percents changed like one time it was 1 blue and 9 red. Then it was 50/50.

They are talking about running the 10 spins 300 times. A student is explaining how to do it on Tinkerplots. The teacher runs it and does a sample distribution. T - What does each dot mean? S- We collect 300 samples of 10 spins.

T- Where have you seen this kind of display before? What kind of display is this? S - In our arm span data. Teacher tells them they can find the mean. She shows them how on Tinkerplots. What was it? S-  50. T-What else could we do to check how precise? S- IQR we could add a hat. She does. T- What is the IQR? S- 20.
Students are now in their groups running theirs 300 times like the teacher ran hers. They are creating a distribution. The teaher has them answering questions on worksheet page 42.
Students continue to work in groups. T- How many spins of the spinner does each dot of the plot mean? S- Each dot represents 10 of the spins. T - So we ran 300 of 10 spins.

T- Why was the median percent 50? S- Because the spinner is a 50/50 chance spinner. T- If every person clicked a median they would get a 50, why? S - Because it is a 50/50 spinner.
She has them turn to page 43 and gives them the instruction to create a new spinner and set the repetitions to 100, run it and plot it like she did.

T - If larger sample size can we get closer to 50/50? S- No T- What do we need to do? S- Collect the statistics of the blue 300 times. Then run it and plot it. T- We need to compare? So how are we comparing these? S- The bottom display has more numbers, each dot is 100. T - Should we look at our mean?  S- The top display is 49.5 the bottom is 50.2. T - What's the difference? S- The bottom has a larger trial size. T - What about the shape? S - it goes up then down.

The students are comparing the two sample distributions the teacher has displayed. T- What about the IQR? S- It is closer together on the bottom display looking at the range of the spins on the number of times it landed on blue. The teacher has them now running their own to compare.
The class is getting a bit rowdy. They are still working on their distributions. T - By showing hands how many of you had an IQR decrease? Some raise their hands. No discussion by students.

Teacher is having the students turn their computers around to show her. Really trying to settle them down. T - What do you think would happen if I had another spinner and I ran it 300 times? S- It would be even more precise than the other it would get closer to the 50%. The bigger we go, that we repeat, the more precise it gets.
S- The more times we run it the more precise we get to the actual percent you have for that spinner. So closer to 50% if it is a 50/50 spinner or 60% if it is a 60/40 spinner.
